            <q>There's nothing woolly about a social conscience. A growing band of social entrepreneurs are lending business brains to social aims &#x2026; Oxford's Said Business School is launching its Skoll Centre of Social Entrepreneurship with a grand-sounding world forum &#x2026; Hyperbole, perhaps. But social entrepreuneurship is in danger of becoming business flavour of the month".</q>
            That suggests that perhaps the notion that people setting up CICs will have nowhere to go for advice is wrong. If this kind of initiative is becoming part of the academic establishment that should be tremendously reassuring to noble Lords who are worried about the matter.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0659P0-05343'>
